  "prompt": "Design-system ticket. Our workshop-registration page failed an accessibility review (labels not associated, errors announced nowhere, no error summary), and I want the fix to be a reusable form kit, not another one-off. Build it as two files next to run_tests.mjs:\n\nform_reducer.ts — the validation state machine, pure TS, no React import. Exports: FieldKind = \"text\" | \"email\" | \"multiline\"; FieldSpec { name, label, kind, required?, maxLength?, hint? }; FieldState { value, touched, error: string | null }; FormState { fields: Record<name, FieldState>, submitAttempted: boolean, status: \"editing\" | \"submitted\" }; FormAction = change {name, value} | blur {name} | submit | reset; plus three functions:\n- validateField(spec, value): trim the value first; checks in order, first failure wins: (1) required and trimmed empty -> \"<label> is required.\" (2) trimmed non-empty, kind email, not shaped like one-@-with-a-dot-after-it (no whitespace, non-empty local part, e.g. ada@example.com passes; ada@example, @example.com, ada lovelace@example.com fail) -> \"<label> must be a valid email address.\" (3) maxLength set and trimmed length strictly over it -> \"<label> must be <maxLength> characters or fewer.\" Otherwise null. Optional empty fields are always fine.\n- initForm(specs): every field { value: \"\", touched: false, error: null } in spec order, submitAttempted false, status \"editing\".\n- createFormReducer(specs) -> (state, action) => state. Semantics: change stores the value and re-validates ONLY if that field is touched or submitAttempted (otherwise error stays as-is — we don't yell while someone is still typing), and any change flips status back to \"editing\". blur marks the field touched and validates its current value. submit validates and touches every field, sets submitAttempted, and sets status \"submitted\" only if everything is clean. reset returns a pristine initForm state. Unknown action types: return the same state object untouched. change/blur naming a field that isn't in the specs: throw RangeError(\"unknown field: <name>\"). The reducer NEVER mutates the state it was given — fresh objects on every transition.\n\naccessible_form.tsx — export function AccessibleForm({ specs, state, legend }). It renders (classes/ids/attributes are the contract, my markup below is normalized):\n<form class=\"acc-form\" novalidate> <fieldset> <legend>{legend}</legend> [error summary] [one block per field, spec order] <button type=\"submit\">Submit</button> </fieldset> [success line] </form>\n- Error summary: only when submitAttempted AND at least one field currently has an error: <div class=\"error-summary\" role=\"alert\" aria-labelledby=\"error-summary-heading\"> <h2 id=\"error-summary-heading\">There is a problem</h2> <ul> one <li><a href=\"#field-<name>\">{error}</a></li> per erroring field, spec order </ul> </div>, placed between the legend and the first field.\n- Each field: <div class=\"form-field\"> <label for=\"field-<name>\">{label}</label>, then if the spec has a hint <p class=\"field-hint\" id=\"field-<name>-hint\">{hint}</p>, then the control, then if the error is SHOWING <p class=\"field-error\" id=\"field-<name>-error\">{error}</p> </div>. An error is showing when it's non-null AND (touched or submitAttempted).\n- The control: multiline -> <textarea>, else <input type=\"email\"|\"text\">. Always id=\"field-<name>\" and name=<name>, always controlled from state (value= — empty string included). When the error is showing add aria-invalid=\"true\" (omit the attribute entirely otherwise). aria-describedby is the space-joined list of hint id then error id, only including the ones that are actually rendered — and the attribute must be OMITTED when that list is empty, not rendered empty.\n- Success: when status is \"submitted\", after the fieldset: <p class=\"form-success\" role=\"status\">Thanks, your details were submitted.</p>. No summary, no field errors in that state (the reducer guarantees it).\n\nAcceptance is `node run_tests.mjs` fully green — the harness (read-only, as usual) shells out to the esbuild binary on PATH, bundles your two files with the React 19.2.7 that's vendored under ./vendor/node_modules, and asserts renderToStaticMarkup output plus reducer transitions. So: server-render only (no effects, no refs, no browser APIs), everything must work offline (no npm install — the vendor tree is already there), and don't sweat JSX prop order, the harness sorts attributes before comparing. TS type annotations, no enums/namespaces.",
  "verify_cmd": "node run_tests.mjs",
  "test_files": ["run_tests.mjs"],
  "notes": "react 19.2.7 + react-dom 19.2.7 + scheduler 0.27.0 (production cjs builds, complete packages minus READMEs) vendored in files/vendor/node_modules. Harness bundles via esbuild binary on PATH (probed v0.28.1), NODE_PATH-based resolution, fully offline at trace time. Bundle output .bundle_out/ is created and removed by the harness itself."
